Lesson 2 - Facets

The plot with chickens is difficult because it shows too much information, but by using an average of all of them together, you hide information, so you want to show as much as possible.

# this is where facet wrap comes in.

# it breaks up a graph into individual plots

facet_wrap()

ggplot(chick_weight) + 
  aes(x = time, y = weight, group = chick, colour = diet) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~ diet)
# within facet wrap, you can specify nrow, ncol, scales

facet_grid

ggplot(chick_weight) + 
  aes(x = time, y = weight, group = chick, colour = diet) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~ diet, ncol = 4)

Hint: geom_histogram is almost the same as geom_bar, but is better suited to plotting continuous data because of the binning.
ggplot(unemployment) + 
geom_histogram(aes(x = age, fill = sex), col = "white") + 
facet_wrap( ~ sex, ncol = 2)
ggplot(unemployment) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = age, fill = sex), col = "white") + 
  facet_wrap(married ~ sex)

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  facet_grid(married ~ sex)

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(unemployment) +

This misrepresents our data

ggplot(unemployment) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = married, fill = dkids), col = "white") + 
  facet_grid(married ~ dkids, scales = "free_y")

It is not terriblt useful on THIS dataset, because the names are short, but it can be good on very long names of bar graphs as it “widens” the x axis
